What I want to talk about is the possibility of a feedback loop: measuring becomes a leading shaper of the subject being measured.

Let’s take economics. Economists are excited: is electronic health record systems leading to so-called big data economics? Economic science at the speed of the internet? Hmmm. As we monitor the economy more and more comprehensively we are even more vulnerable to data-driven economic shocks. The revelation of hidden facts through always gathering information is the opposite of giving confidence. Imagine we were rationale. Then all information is simultaneously revealed as information is accumulated. Now we are rational. That sounds better but is not the case in reality. As economic crises become more and economic science clearer. As some Open Data projects have shown with the specific question of measuring economic well being big data does not mean that we measure better. The same applies to the medical body. As we create vast datasets to deliver the holy grail of personalised medicine we also enter the risk of another public medical melt down or what is Thomas Pynchon has written: ‘If they can keep you asking the wrong questions, they don’t have to worry about the answers.’

So the real question becomes: what are the effects of increased informating on the society and the individual at the beginning of the 21st century? Big data is a question of control but at the same time of control escaping: with increased informating becomes ungovernable or to paraphrase the Net Firewall we build may one day bake rise to million-headed monsters that’ll turn and swallow us up. When measurement becomes the bulb the thing it is suppose to measure the less do we know.

