Constructivism

Unlike the functionalist approach I mentioned above constructivism accentuates two main concepts informing my interactive design. The first is the idea of semiotical aesthetic relations as introduced by Susanne Langer (1895–1985). Secondly the concept of the Second-order cybernetics by Heinz von Foerster (1911-2002).

Semiotic Theory by Susanne Langer

“A theory of the mind is the problem and the criterion of aesthetics” (Langer 1953). For Langer semiotics is the art of aesthetics: that uniting the sensability with the symbolisation of meaning. Langer coins the term ‘presentational-symbols’ to describe the mind’s ability to think primarily through feelings (25). The arts are mind systems: the core of the arts is the incarnation of ‘feeling’: a coherent image or form that is given (through artistic meaning or the semiotics translation of meaning) with the intention to transfer and communicate but existing neither in the mind of the creator nor that of the recipient (Langer 1953 23). Therefore the artistic experience is the experience of ‘presentational-symbols’ (Schirrmacher 1956: 51). For Langer thinking is characterised by the worldview that the symbolic content is not extracted but exists as an idea in a ‘kind of blend of idea and impression’(Langer 1953 142). She is calling the symbol device ‘analogous’ (Langer 1953 272). Symbols are responsible to trigger mind operations; all we know is a symbol for (as representation of) something else or another (Langer 1953 65).

Second-order cybernetics by Heinz von Foerster

